<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n33335e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33335e">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33335e"> 335(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> alulae / tipula / haltere</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">THE CRANE-FLY. When the fly is on the wing these halteres, or &ldquo;balancers,&rdquo; are in rapid motion, and possibly serve some sensory purpose such as was indicated in the case of the House-Fly. Unlike that insect, however, the <mark>alulae</mark> of the <i>Tipula</i> are almost extinct. A mere speck at the inset of the <mark>haltere</mark> is the only indication of them. <small> J.H. Crabtree, <a name="JHCW" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JHCW"><cite title="source">Wonders of Insect Life</cite></a> (n.d.) 89</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In a large number of Diptera, an incision in the posterior margin of the wing, near the base, marks off a small lobe, the posterior lobe or <mark>alula</mark>. </mm> </dd></dl>
